column5: and agricultural organization (fao), saline soils affect 6% of the world’s land mass,&#10
column6: equivalent to 831 million hectares. salinity decreases the external osmotic potential in soil&#10
column7: solution, causing ion accumulations and reactive oxygen species (ros) production [6]. salt&#10
column8: (nacl) damage can cause the necrosis of older leaves, enhancing na+ influx and k+ leakage that leads to an elevated na+/k+ ratio in plant cells [7,8]. increased salinity alters the&#10
column9: plants’ morphology, physiology and metabolism through increased ion toxicity that leads&#10
column10: to decreases in the availability of essential elements such as phosphorus and calcium, as&#10
column11: well as protein synthesis and metabolism of lipids [9]. these result in premature senescence&#10
column12: and the loss of photosynthetic efficiency that lead to reductions in carbon assimilation and&#10
column13: yield. although plants have the capacity to generate various forms of antioxidants that&#10
column14: can alleviate oxidative damages, there is a need to further investigate other exogenous&#10
column15: applications, including the use of phytoprotectants such as brassinolide (bl), to boost&#10
column16: plants’ oxidative defence against salinity stress.
